{"title_page": "New York Guardians", "text_new": "{{for|the team from the original XFL|New York/New Jersey Hitmen}}\n{{short description|XFL (2020) team based in New York City, New York}}\n{{Infobox sports team  \n| logo = New York Guardians.png\n| pixels = 200px\n| founded = 2018\n| league = [[XFL (2020)|XFL]]\n| history = '''New York Guardians (2020\u2013present)'''\n| division = East<ref name=\"kmph\">{{cite news |title=FOX Sports announces 2020 XFL schedule |url=https://kmph.com/sports/content/fox-sports-announces-2020-xfl-schedule |accessdate=February 4, 2020 |work=KMPH |date=January 7, 2020}}</ref>\n| stadium = [[MetLife Stadium]]<br />[[East Rutherford, New Jersey]]\n| city = [[New Jersey]]\n| website = {{URL|https://www.xfl.com/en-US/teams/new-york}}\n| colors = Black, grey, red<ref>{{cite press release|title=New York Guardians' uniforms, helmet|url=https://www.xfl.com/en-US/articles/new-york-guardians-uniforms-reveal|website=XFL.com|date=December 3, 2019|access-date=December 12, 2019}}</ref><br />{{color box|#000000}} {{color box|#A4A3A8}} {{color box|#CF143F}}\n| owner = [[Vince McMahon|Alpha Entertainment, LLC]]\n| president = Janet Duch<ref>https://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Daily/Issues/2019/04/16/People-and-Pop-Culture/XFL-Duch.aspx</ref>\n| gm = Kevin Gilbride\n| coach = [[Kevin Gilbride]]\n| championships = \n| titles = \n| current = 2020 New York Guardians season\n}}\n\nThe '''New York Guardians''' are a professional [[American football]] team based in the [[New York metropolitan area]]. The team is an owned-and-operated member of the new [[XFL (2020)|XFL]] founded by [[Vince McMahon]]'s Alpha Entertainment and plays its home games at [[MetLife Stadium]] in [[East Rutherford, New Jersey]].\n\nThe team is coached by [[Kevin Gilbride]], a longtime offensive coordinator in the [[National Football League]] (most recently with a ten-season stint with the [[New York Giants]]). Gilbride came out of a six-year retirement to join the XFL; his hiring was announced April 16, 2019.<ref>https://www.msn.com/en-ca/sports/nfl/report-xfl-new-york-team-to-be-coached-by-kevin-gilbride/ar-BBVXYZ8</ref>\n\nThe team's name and colors were revealed on August 21, 2019, as part of a league-wide announcement.\n\n==Background and market overview==\nNew York is one of two metropolitan areas, the other being [[Los Angeles Wildcats (XFL)|Los Angeles]], to have hosted teams in both the original [[XFL (2001)|XFL]] in 2001 and the 2020 XFL; the [[New York/New Jersey Hitmen]] were the Guardians' predecessors in the previous league.\n\nThe [[New York metropolitan area]] has 16 professional teams in some form or another, including three NHL teams, two NBA teams and two MLS teams whose seasons substantially overlap with the XFL's.<ref name=sportbusiness>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportbusiness.com/news/oliver-luck-so-far-so-good-in-xfl-but-la-and-new-york-crowds-need-to-improve/|title=\nOliver Luck: So far, so good in XFL \u2013 but LA and New York crowds need to improve|first=Bob|last=Williams|work=SportBusiness.com|date=March 1, 2020|access-date=March 1, 2020}}</ref> The Guardians (despite carrying a New York brand) are locally marketing themselves as a New Jersey franchise to differentiate themselves from the other teams in the region.<ref>Gabrielle Saulsbery (November 18, 2019). [https://njbiz.com/guardian-state/ Guardian state]. ''NJ BIZ''. Retrieved November 18, 2019.</ref> MetLife Stadium is the largest venue in the XFL; the league has been public in its desire to find a smaller venue, mentioning [[Red Bull Arena (New Jersey)|Red Bull Arena]] as a potential venue for 2021.<ref name=sportbusiness/>\n\n== 2020 ==\n[[File:New York Guardians vs. Dallas Renegades 2020 28 (New York on offense).jpg|thumb|New York in action against [[2020 Dallas Renegades season|Dallas]] in 2020]]\n\nThe Guardians won the first game in franchise history, topping the [[Tampa Bay Vipers]] 23-3 at MetLife Stadium. Quarterback Matt McGloin scored the first touchdown in team history on their first possession, a one-yard score that put them up 6-0. McGloin would later find [[Colby Pearson]] for a passing touchdown. Defensively, the Guardians forced three turnovers, including a fumble return for a touchdown by [[Jamar Summers]]. Tampa Bay reached the [[Red zone (gridiron football)|red zone]] five times, but emerged only with a field goal thanks to a standout defensive effort.\n\nThe Guardians' first road game saw them become the victims of the first shutout in the new XFL's history, as they fell to the [[DC Defenders]] by a 27-0 final at [[Audi Field]]. The game became notable for a McGloin sideline interview with ABC/ESPN's [[Dianna Russini]], in which he was very critical of the team's offensive gameplan. McGloin was eventually pulled from the game for backup [[Marquise Williams]] in the second half. \n\nNew York's next game was a visit to [[The Dome at America's Center]] to take on the [[St. Louis BattleHawks]]. Another one-sided loss awaited the Guardians, as they fell by a 29-9 final in St. Louis' home opener. McGloin was injured on the Guardians' first possession. He returned to the game, but missed the entire second half. New York did manage to end a streak of 26 consecutive possessions without a touchdown when third-string quarterback [[Luis Perez (American football)|Luis Perez]] found [[Austin Duke]] for an eight-yard score in the fourth quarter. \n\nWith McGloin out with an injury, Perez was the Guardians' starting quarterback for their Week 4 return to MetLife Stadium. Assisted by a strong rushing attack, Perez was able to guide the Guardians to a 17-14 victory over the [[Los Angeles Wildcats (XFL)|Los Angeles Wildcats]]. The Guardians tallied 122 yards on the ground, led by a tally of 82 from [[Darius Victor]]. New York took the lead for good on a 47-yard field goal from [[Matthew McCrane]], which was set up by a Summers interception. [[Jarrell Owens]] led the way defensively for the Guardians with two sacks and a blocked field goal. \n\nPerez earned another start when the Guardians hit the road again, taking on the [[Dallas Renegades]] at [[Globe Life Park in Arlington]]. The Guardians would go on to put up their most dominant effort of the season, crushing the Renegades by a 30-12 final. New York's key to victory was a series of 21 unanswered points in the third quarter. Williams came in to score a rushing touchdown from one yard out before Perez hooked up with Pearson for an 80-yard touchdown pass, the longest play in Guardians history. Linebacker [[Ryan Mueller]] capped the barrage off by returning an interception for a touchdown, the Guardians' second defensive score of the season. New York once again had a stellar rushing day, earning 144 yards on the ground. Victor once again led the way, this time with 58 of those yards.\n\nThe Guardians were set to take on the undefeated [[Houston Roughnecks]] at MetLife Stadium prior to the XFL's decision to suspend its season due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]. New York finished their inaugural season with a 3-2 record and engaged in a three-way tie for first place in the XFL's East Division.\n\n==Roster==\n{{New York Guardians roster}}\n\n==Staff==\n{{New York XFL team staff}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{XFL (2020)}}\n{{NewYorksports}}\n{{NewJerseysports}}\n[[Category:New York Guardians| ]]\n[[Category:2018 establishments in New York City]]\n[[Category:American football teams in New Jersey]]\n[[Category:American football teams established in 2018]]\n[[Category:Sports in East Rutherford, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:XFL teams]]\n{{amfoot-team-stub}}\n{{NewYork-sport-team-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{for|the team from the original XFL|New York/New Jersey Hitmen}}\n{{short description|XFL (2020) team based in New York City, New York}}\n{{Infobox sports team  \n| logo = New York Guardians.png\n| pixels = 200px\n| founded = 2018\n| league = [[XFL (2020)|XFL]]\n| history = '''New York Guardians (2020\u2013present)'''\n| division = East<ref name=\"kmph\">{{cite news |title=FOX Sports announces 2020 XFL schedule |url=https://kmph.com/sports/content/fox-sports-announces-2020-xfl-schedule |accessdate=February 4, 2020 |work=KMPH |date=January 7, 2020}}</ref>\n| stadium = [[MetLife Stadium]]<br />[[East Rutherford, New Jersey]]\n| city = [[New Jersey]]\n| website = {{URL|https://www.xfl.com/en-US/teams/new-york}}\n| colors = Black, grey, red<ref>{{cite press release|title=New York Guardians' uniforms, helmet|url=https://www.xfl.com/en-US/articles/new-york-guardians-uniforms-reveal|website=XFL.com|date=December 3, 2019|access-date=December 12, 2019}}</ref><br />{{color box|#000000}} {{color box|#A4A3A8}} {{color box|#CF143F}}\n| owner = [[Vince McMahon|Alpha Entertainment, LLC]]\n| president = Janet Duch<ref>https://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Daily/Issues/2019/04/16/People-and-Pop-Culture/XFL-Duch.aspx</ref>\n| gm = Kevin Gilbride\n| coach = [[Kevin Gilbride]]\n| championships = \n| titles = \n| current = 2020 New York Guardians season\n}}\n\nThe '''New York Guardians''' are a professional [[American football]] team based in the [[New York metropolitan area]]. The team is an owned-and-operated member of the new [[XFL (2020)|XFL]] founded by [[Vince McMahon]]'s Alpha Entertainment and plays its home games at [[MetLife Stadium]] in [[East Rutherford, New Jersey]].\n\nThe team is coached by [[Kevin Gilbride]], a longtime offensive coordinator in the [[National Football League]] (most recently with a ten-season stint with the [[New York Giants]]). Gilbride came out of a six-year retirement to join the XFL; his hiring was announced April 16, 2019.<ref>https://www.msn.com/en-ca/sports/nfl/report-xfl-new-york-team-to-be-coached-by-kevin-gilbride/ar-BBVXYZ8</ref>\n\nThe team's name and colors were revealed on August 21, 2019, as part of a league-wide announcement.\n\n==Background and market overview==\nNew York is one of two metropolitan areas, the other being [[Los Angeles Wildcats (XFL)|Los Angeles]], to have hosted teams in both the original [[XFL (2001)|XFL]] in 2001 and the 2020 XFL; the [[New York/New Jersey Hitmen]] were the Guardians' predecessors in the previous league.\n\nThe [[New York metropolitan area]] has 16 professional teams in some form or another, including three NHL teams, two NBA teams and two MLS teams whose seasons substantially overlap with the XFL's.<ref name=sportbusiness>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportbusiness.com/news/oliver-luck-so-far-so-good-in-xfl-but-la-and-new-york-crowds-need-to-improve/|title=\nOliver Luck: So far, so good in XFL \u2013 but LA and New York crowds need to improve|first=Bob|last=Williams|work=SportBusiness.com|date=March 1, 2020|access-date=March 1, 2020}}</ref> The Guardians (despite carrying a New York brand) are locally marketing themselves as a New Jersey franchise to differentiate themselves from the other teams in the region.<ref>Gabrielle Saulsbery (November 18, 2019). [https://njbiz.com/guardian-state/ Guardian state]. ''NJ BIZ''. Retrieved November 18, 2019.</ref> MetLife Stadium is the largest venue in the XFL; the league has been public in its desire to find a smaller venue, mentioning [[Red Bull Arena (New Jersey)|Red Bull Arena]] as a potential venue for 2021.<ref name=sportbusiness/>\n\n== 2020 ==\n[[File:New York Guardians vs. Dallas Renegades 2020 28 (New York on offense).jpg|thumb|New York in action against [[2020 Dallas Renegades season|Dallas]] in 2020]]\n\nThe Guardians won the first game in franchise history, topping the [[Tampa Bay Vipers]] 23-3 at MetLife Stadium. Quarterback Matt McGloin scored the first touchdown in team history on their first possession, a one-yard score that put them up 6-0. McGloin would later find [[Colby Pearson]] for a passing touchdown. Defensively, the Guardians forced three turnovers, including a fumble return for a touchdown by [[Jamar Summers]]. Tampa Bay reached the [[red zone]] five times, but emerged only with a field goal thanks to a standout defensive effort.\n\nThe Guardians' first road game saw them become the victims of the first shutout in the new XFL's history, as they fell to the [[DC Defenders]] by a 27-0 final at [[Audi Field]]. The game became notable for a McGloin sideline interview with ABC/ESPN's [[Dianna Russini]], in which he was very critical of the team's offensive gameplan. McGloin was eventually pulled from the game for backup [[Marquise Williams]] in the second half. \n\nNew York's next game was a visit to [[The Dome at America's Center]] to take on the [[St. Louis BattleHawks]]. Another one-sided loss awaited the Guardians, as they fell by a 29-9 final in St. Louis' home opener. McGloin was injured on the Guardians' first possession. He returned to the game, but missed the entire second half. New York did manage to end a streak of 26 consecutive possessions without a touchdown when third-string quarterback [[Luis Perez (American football)|Luis Perez]] found [[Austin Duke]] for an eight-yard score in the fourth quarter. \n\nWith McGloin out with an injury, Perez was the Guardians' starting quarterback for their Week 4 return to MetLife Stadium. Assisted by a strong rushing attack, Perez was able to guide the Guardians to a 17-14 victory over the [[Los Angeles Wildcats (XFL)|Los Angeles Wildcats]]. The Guardians tallied 122 yards on the ground, led by a tally of 82 from [[Darius Victor]]. New York took the lead for good on a 47-yard field goal from [[Matthew McCrane]], which was set up by a Summers interception. [[Jarrell Owens]] led the way defensively for the Guardians with two sacks and a blocked field goal. \n\nPerez earned another start when the Guardians hit the road again, taking on the [[Dallas Renegades]] at [[Globe Life Park in Arlington]]. The Guardians would go on to put up their most dominant effort of the season, crushing the Renegades by a 30-12 final. New York's key to victory was a series of 21 unanswered points in the third quarter. Williams came in to score a rushing touchdown from one yard out before Perez hooked up with Pearson for an 80-yard touchdown pass, the longest play in Guardians history. Linebacker [[Ryan Mueller]] capped the barrage off by returning an interception for a touchdown, the Guardians' second defensive score of the season. New York once again had a stellar rushing day, earning 144 yards on the ground. Victor once again led the way, this time with 58 of those yards.\n\nThe Guardians were set to take on the undefeated [[Houston Roughnecks]] at MetLife Stadium prior to the XFL's decision to suspend its season due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]. New York finished their inaugural season with a 3-2 record and engaged in a three-way tie for first place in the XFL's East Division.\n\n==Roster==\n{{New York Guardians roster}}\n\n==Staff==\n{{New York XFL team staff}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{XFL (2020)}}\n{{NewYorksports}}\n{{NewJerseysports}}\n[[Category:New York Guardians| ]]\n[[Category:2018 establishments in New York City]]\n[[Category:American football teams in New Jersey]]\n[[Category:American football teams established in 2018]]\n[[Category:Sports in East Rutherford, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:XFL teams]]\n{{amfoot-team-stub}}\n{{NewYork-sport-team-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toRed Zone(link changed toRed zone (gridiron football)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_York_Guardians"}
{"title_page": "Great American Novel", "text_new": "{{short description|Concept of a novel of high literary merit}}\n{{About|the Great American Novel as a concept}}\n{{Use American English|date = April 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2016}}\n\nThe term '''Great American Novel''' ('''GAN''') refers to a [[Western Canon|canonical]] novel that is thought to have captured the spirit of American life. These novels are generally written by [[American literature|Americans]] and deal in some way with the question of America's [[Culture of the United States|national character]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}} The Great American Novel is sometimes considered America's equivalent of the [[national epic]].{{By whom|date=February 2020}}\n\nThere is no consensus on which novel or novels deserve to be called the Great American Novel. Practically, many academics use the term to refer to a small number of books that have historically been the nexus of discussion, including ''[[Moby-Dick]]'', ''[[Adventures of Huckleberry Finn]]'' and ''[[The Great Gatsby]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eW7B3RwuxIo&t=1080s|title=The Great American Novel|last=Elliott|first=Michael|date=November 16, 2016|website=|type=Video|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Hubert Dreyfus - Melville's Moby Dick|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eq5LDSZDr2E|language=en|access-date=2019-11-04}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nWhile [[fiction]] was written in [[British America|colonial North America]] as early as the 17th century, it was not until a distinct U.S. identity developed in the 18th century that works classified as [[American literature|U.S. literature]] began. The U.S. identity as a nation was reflected alongside the development of its literature.{{citation needed|date = December 2013}}\n\nThe term ''Great American Novel'' comes directly from the title of an 1868 essay<ref>{{Citation|last=DeForest|first=John|author-link=John William DeForest|date=9 January 1868|title=The Great American Novel|periodical=The Nation|place=New York|url=http://utc.iath.virginia.edu/articles/n2ar39at.html|accessdate=October 11, 2010}}</ref> by [[American Civil War]] novelist [[John William De Forest]]. He defined the Great American novel as \"the picture of the ordinary emotions and manners of American existence\".<ref>{{Citation|last=DeForest|first=John|author-link=John William DeForest|date=9 January 1868|title=The Great American Novel|periodical=The Nation|place=New York|url=http://utc.iath.virginia.edu/articles/n2ar39at.html|accessdate=October 11, 2010}}</ref> Although early Great American Novel candidates were typically chosen by academics and scholars, the concept has opened up in recent years. [[Lawrence Buell]], Professor of American Literature Emeritus at [[Harvard University]], said that in the 21st century \"the dream of the GAN is less in the hands of credentialed critics and scholars to determine than the result of a complex, messy interaction among them, readers at large, the literary entrepreneurialism of the writers themselves, the publishing and education industries, and self-accredited freelance journalists and bloggers.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Dream of the Great American Novel|last=Buell|first=Lawrence|publisher=Harvard University Press|year=2014|isbn=9780674726321|location=Cambridge, Massachusetts|pages=9|oclc=871257583}}</ref>\n\nIn modern usage, the meaning of the term is often [[Literal and figurative language|figurative]] and represents a [[Western canon|canonical]] piece of literature, making it a literary benchmark emblematic of what defines U.S. literature in a given era.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Claimants==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"margin:auto;\"\n!Publication year\n!Novel\n!Author\n|-\n|1826\n|''{{sort|Last of the Mohicans|[[The Last of the Mohicans]]}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1957&dat=19920921&id=lsBKAAAAIBAJ&sjid=wOkMAAAAIBAJ&pg=2923,5076520&hl=en|title='Last of the Mohicans' was first great American novel|last=Italie|first=Hillel|accessdate=October 14, 2015}}</ref>''\n|[[James Fenimore Cooper]] \n|-\n|1850\n|''{{sort|Scarlet Letter|[[The Scarlet Letter]]}}''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/books/the-dream-of-the-great-american-novel-by-lawrence-buell/2011522.article|title=The Dream of the Great American Novel|last=Buell|first=Lawrence|accessdate=October 14, 2015 |quote=There are, Buell says, four main types of potential Great American Novels. Nathaniel Hawthorne's ''The Scarlet Letter'' epitomises the first \u2013 a cultural 'master narrative', identified as such by the number of reinterpretations and imitations that follow in its wake.}}</ref>\n|[[Nathaniel Hawthorne]] \n|-\n|1851\n|''[[Moby-Dick]]''<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://alh.oxfordjournals.org/content/20/1-2/132.short?rss=1&ssource=mfc|title=The Unkillable Dream of the Great American Novel: Moby-Dick as Test Case|last=Buell|first=Lawrence|journal=American Literary History |volume=20 |issue=1\u20132 |pages=132\u2013155|accessdate=October 26, 2010|doi=10.1093/alh/ajn005|year=2008}}</ref>\n|[[Herman Melville]] \n|-\n|1852\n|''[[Uncle Tom's Cabin]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neh.gov/humanities/2013/marchapril/feature/the-first-great-american-novel|title=The First Great American Novel|last=Fuller|first=Randall|accessdate=October 14, 2015}}</ref>\n|[[Harriet Beecher Stowe]] \n|-\n|1876\n|''{{sort|Adventures of Tom Sawyer|[[The Adventures of Tom Sawyer]]}}''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://americanenglish.state.gov/resources/adventures-tom-sawyer|title=The Adventures of Tom Sawyer|last=Department of State|first=United States|accessdate=October 14, 2015 |quote=Considered one of the great American novels&nbsp;...}}</ref>\n|[[Mark Twain]] \n|-\n|1884\n|''[[Adventures of Huckleberry Finn]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.americanheritage.com/content/one-hundred-years-huck-finn|title=One Hundred Years of Huck Finn|last=Brown|first=Robert B.|date=June\u2013July 1984|publisher=American Heritage Publishing|accessdate=December 10, 2011 |quote=It was called the 'great American novel' as early as 1891 by the English writer Andrew Lang&nbsp;... }}</ref>\n|[[Mark Twain]]\n|-\n|1925\n|''{{sort|Great Gatsby|[[The Great Gatsby]]}}''<ref>Emory Elliott et al. (eds.) (1991). ''[https://archive.org/details/columbiahistoryo00elli/page/323 <!-- quote=\"Great American Novel\" \"Great Gatsby\". --> The Columbia History of the American Novel]''. Columbia University Press. p. 323. \"The Great Gatsby (1925), a work still frequently nominated as 'the great American novel'&nbsp;...\"</ref>\n|[[F. Scott Fitzgerald]] \n|-\n|1925\n|''[[An American Tragedy]]''<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title = The Dream of the Great American Novel|last = Buell|first = Lawrence|publisher = Belknap|year = 2014|isbn = |location = |pages = }}</ref>\n|[[Theodore Dreiser]] \n|-\n|1932\n|''[[Light in August]]''<ref>{{cite news|author=C. E. Morgan |date=August 6, 2012 |title='Light in August' is Faulkner's Great American Novel |work=The Daily Beast |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2012/08/16/c-e-morgan-light-in-august-is-faulkner-s-great-american-novel.html |access-date=October 5, 2016}}</ref>\n|[[William Faulkner]] \n|-\n|1934\n|''[[Tropic of Cancer (novel)|Tropic of Cancer]]''<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://groveatlantic.com/book/tropic-of-cancer/|title=Tropic of Cancer |first=Henry |last=Miller |publisher=Grove Atlantic|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/reviews/book-of-a-lifetime-tropic-of-cancer-by-henry-miller-1719362.html|title=Book Of A Lifetime: Tropic of Cancer, By Henry Miller|work=The Independent|last=Morrison|first=Ewan|access-date=2018-12-02|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n|[[Henry Miller]] \n|-\n|1936\n|''[[Absalom, Absalom!]]''<ref>{{Cite news | last = Hirsch | first = Arthur | title = The real great American Novel: 'Absalom, 