rican novel that everyone keeps waiting for but it has been written now.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last = Nixon | first = Rob | title = The Grapes of Wrath | work = This Month Spotlight | publisher = Turner Classic Movies | url = http://www.tcm.com/thismonth/article.jsp?cid=182376&mainArticleId=252903 | accessdate =September 22, 2010}} Nixon quotes John Springer, author of ''The Fondas'' (Citadel, 1973), a book about [[Henry Fonda]] and his role in film version of ''[[The Grapes of Wrath (film)|The Grapes of Wrath]]'': \"The Great American Novel made one of the few enduring Great American Motion Pictures.\"</ref>\n|[[John Steinbeck]]\n|-\n|1951\n|''{{sort|Catcher in the Rye|[[The Catcher in the Rye]]}}''<ref>{{cite news | last = McGrath | first = Charles |title= J. D. Salinger, Literary Recluse, Dies at 91 | work = New York Times | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2010/01/29/books/29salinger.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0 | date =January 28, 2010}}</ref>\n|[[J. D. Salinger]] \n|-\n|1952\n|''[[Invisible Man]]''<ref>{{cite news | last = Giles | first = Patrick | title = The Great American Novel | work = Los Angeles Times | url = http://articles.latimes.com/2002/sep/15/books/bk-giles15 | date=September 15, 2002}}</ref>\n|[[Ralph Ellison]]\n|-\n|1953\n|''{{sort|Adventures of Augie March|[[The Adventures of Augie March]]}}''<ref>{{cite news | last = Amis | first = Martin | authorlink=Martin Amis | title = Review | work = The Atlantic Monthly | url = http://www.powells.com/biblio?isbn=9780140281606 |quote=''The Adventures of Augie March'' is the Great American Novel. Search no further. All the trails went cold 42 years ago. The quest did what quests very rarely do; it ended.}}</ref>\n|[[Saul Bellow]] \n|-\n|1955\n|''[[Lolita]]''<ref>{{cite web | last = Williams | first = Mary Elizabeth | title = ''Lolita'' by Vladimir Nabokov | work = Personal Best | publisher = Salon | url = http://www.salon.com/1996/09/30/nabokov_4/ | accessdate = January 26, 2013 |quote=Some say the Great American Novel is ''Huckleberry Finn'', some say it's ''The Jungle'', some say it's ''The Great Gatsby''. \u2013 Vladimir Nabokov's ''Lolita''}}.</ref><ref>{{Cite book | last = Jameson | first = Frederick | title = The Seeds of Time | publisher = Columbia University Press | year = 1996 | location = New York | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=hXsWr85Hg9QC&lpg=PA147&dq=%E2%80%9Cwhich%20thereby%20at%20once%20became%20The%20Great%20American%20Novel%E2%80%9D&pg=PA147#v=onepage&q=%E2%80%9Cwhich%20thereby%20at%20once%20became%20The%20Great%20American%20Novel%E2%80%9D&f=false |quote=These are familiar features of daily life in the super state from which, it should be noted, high modernism in the United States \u2013 in theory and in practice alike, fifties aestheticism organized around Pound and Henry James and Wallace Stevens and the New Criticism \u2013 was in desperate flight; of our great modern writers, only Nabokov handled this kind of material, in ''Lolita'', which thereby at once became The Great American Novel,\u2013 but of course he was a foreigner to begin with. |pages=146\u2013147| isbn = 9780231080583 }}</ref><ref>Nabakov is generally regarded as a Russian writer, even when he used the English language: {{cite book|last1=Rampton|first1=David|title=Vladimir Nabokov: a critical study of the novels|date=1984|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|isbn=0521257107|edition=1. publ.}}</ref>\n|[[Vladimir Nabokov]] \n|-\n|1960\n|''[[To Kill a Mockingbird]]''<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.usatoday.com/life/books/news/2010-07-08-mockingbird08_CV_N.htm | work=USA Today | title='To Kill a Mockingbird': Endearing, enduring at 50 years | first=Maria | last=Puente | date=July 8, 2010 |quote=It is Lee's only book and one of the handful that could earn the title of Great American Novel.}} (Lee has since published a sequel, ''[[Go Set a Watchman]]''.)</ref>\n|[[Harper Lee]]\n|-\n|1971\n|''[[Fear and Loathing in Las Vegas]]''<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.businessinsider.com/great-american-novel-locations-map-hip-2015-11?r=DE&IR=T | work=Business Insider | title=This map shows where 42 of the greatest American novels took place | first=Kevin | last=Loria | date=December 6, 2015 |quote= #31 Fear and Loathing in Las Vegas, Las Vegas, NV}} </ref>\n|[[Hunter S. Thompson]]\n|-\n|1985\n|''[[Blood Meridian]]''<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.readersdigest.co.uk/culture/books/meet-the-author/william-dalrymple-blood-meridian-is-the-great-american-novel\n| title=Blood Meridian is the Great American Novel| first=William | last=Dalrymple |publisher = Reader's Digest |quote=McCarthy\u2019s descriptive powers make him the best prose stylist working today, and this book the Great American Novel.}} </ref>\n|[[Cormac McCarthy]]\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Novels}}\n*[[National epic]]\n*[[The American Scholar]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{Cite journal\n| last = Buell\n| first = Lawrence\n| title = American literature's holy grail: The hunt for the Great American Novel\n| accessdate = February 16, 2014\n| url = http://www.salon.com/2014/02/16/american_literatures_holy_grail_the_hunt_for_the_great_american_novel/\n|journal = Salon\n}}\n* [[Lawrence Buell|Buell, Lawrence]]. (2014). ''The Dream of the Great American Novel''. Cambridge, Massachusetts and London: The Belknap Press of Harvard University Press. {{ISBN|9780674051157}}\n*Brown, Herbert R. \"The Great American Novel.\" ''American Literature'' 7.1 (1935): 1\u201314.\n*Knox, George. \"The Great American Novel: Final Chapter.\" ''American Quarterly'' 21.4 (1969): 667\u2013682.\n\n[[Category:American literature]]\n[[Category:American novels]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Concept of a novel of high literary merit}}\n{{About|the Great American Novel as a concept}}\n{{Use American English|date = April 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2016}}\n\nThe term '''Great American Novel''' ('''GAN''') refers to a [[Western Canon|canonical]] novel that is thought to have captured the spirit of American life. These novels are generally written by [[American literature|Americans]] and deal in some way with the question of America's [[Culture of the United States|national character]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}} The Great American Novel is sometimes considered America's equivalent of the [[national epic]].{{By whom|date=February 2020}}\n\nThere is no consensus on which novel or novels deserve to be called the Great American Novel. Practically, many academics use the term to refer to a small number of books that have historically been the nexus of discussion, including ''[[Moby-Dick]]'', ''[[Adventures of Huckleberry Finn]]'' and ''[[The Great Gatsby]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eW7B3RwuxIo&t=1080s|title=The Great American Novel|last=Elliott|first=Michael|date=November 16, 2016|website=|type=Video|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Hubert Dreyfus - Melville's Moby Dick|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eq5LDSZDr2E|language=en|access-date=2019-11-04}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nWhile [[fiction]] was written in [[British America|colonial North America]] as early as the 17th century, it was not until a distinct U.S. identity developed in the 18th century that works classified as [[American literature|U.S. literature]] began. The U.S. identity as a nation was reflected alongside the development of its literature.{{citation needed|date = December 2013}}\n\nThe term ''Great American Novel'' comes directly from the title of an 1868 essay<ref>{{Citation|last=DeForest|first=John|author-link=John William DeForest|date=9 January 1868|title=The Great American Novel|periodical=The Nation|place=New York|url=http://utc.iath.virginia.edu/articles/n2ar39at.html|accessdate=October 11, 2010}}</ref> by [[American Civil War]] novelist [[John William De Forest]]. He defined the Great American novel as \"the picture of the ordinary emotions and manners of American existence\".<ref>{{Citation|last=DeForest|first=John|author-link=John William DeForest|date=9 January 1868|title=The Great American Novel|periodical=The Nation|place=New York|url=http://utc.iath.virginia.edu/articles/n2ar39at.html|accessdate=October 11, 2010}}</ref> Although early Great American Novel candidates were typically chosen by academics and scholars, the concept has opened up in recent years. [[Lawrence Buell]], Professor of American Literature Emeritus at [[Harvard University]], said that in the 21st century \"the dream of the GAN is less in the hands of credentialed critics and scholars to determine than the result of a complex, messy interaction among them, readers at large, the literary entrepreneurialism of the writers themselves, the publishing and education industries, and self-accredited freelance journalists and bloggers.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Dream of the Great American Novel|last=Buell|first=Lawrence|publisher=Harvard University Press|year=2014|isbn=9780674726321|location=Cambridge, Massachusetts|pages=9|oclc=871257583}}</ref>\n\nIn modern usage, the meaning of the term is often [[Literal and figurative language|figurative]] and represents a [[Western canon|canonical]] piece of literature, making it a literary benchmark emblematic of what defines U.S. literature in a given era.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Claimants==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"margin:auto;\"\n!Publication year\n!Novel\n!Author\n|-\n|1826\n|''{{sort|Last of the Mohicans|[[The Last of the Mohicans]]}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1957&dat=19920921&id=lsBKAAAAIBAJ&sjid=wOkMAAAAIBAJ&pg=2923,5076520&hl=en|title='Last of the Mohicans' was first great American novel|last=Italie|first=Hillel|accessdate=October 14, 2015}}</ref>''\n|[[James Fenimore Cooper]] \n|-\n|1850\n|''{{sort|Scarlet Letter|[[The Scarlet Letter]]}}''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/books/the-dream-of-the-great-american-novel-by-lawrence-buell/2011522.article|title=The Dream of the Great American Novel|last=Buell|first=Lawrence|accessdate=October 14, 2015 |quote=There are, Buell says, four main types of potential Great American Novels. Nathaniel Hawthorne's ''The Scarlet Letter'' epitomises the first \u2013 a cultural 'master narrative', identified as such by the number of reinterpretations and imitations that follow in its wake.}}</ref>\n|[[Nathaniel Hawthorne]] \n|-\n|1851\n|''[[Moby-Dick]]''<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://alh.oxfordjournals.org/content/20/1-2/132.short?rss=1&ssource=mfc|title=The Unkillable Dream of the Great American Novel: Moby-Dick as Test Case|last=Buell|first=Lawrence|journal=American Literary History |volume=20 |issue=1\u20132 |pages=132\u2013155|accessdate=October 26, 2010|doi=10.1093/alh/ajn005|year=2008}}</ref>\n|[[Herman Melville]] \n|-\n|1852\n|''[[Uncle Tom's Cabin]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neh.gov/humanities/2013/marchapril/feature/the-first-great-american-novel|title=The First Great American Novel|last=Fuller|first=Randall|accessdate=October 14, 2015}}</ref>\n|[[Harriet Beecher Stowe]] \n|-\n|1876\n|''{{sort|Adventures of Tom Sawyer|[[The Adventures of Tom Sawyer]]}}''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://americanenglish.state.gov/resources/adventures-tom-sawyer|title=The Adventures of Tom Sawyer|last=Department of State|first=United States|accessdate=October 14, 2015 |quote=Considered one of the great American novels&nbsp;...}}</ref>\n|[[Mark Twain]] \n|-\n|1884\n|''[[Adventures of Huckleberry Finn]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.americanheritage.com/content/one-hundred-years-huck-finn|title=One Hundred Years of Huck Finn|last=Brown|first=Robert B.|date=June\u2013July 1984|publisher=American Heritage Publishing|accessdate=December 10, 2011 |quote=It was called the 'great American novel' as early as 1891 by the English writer Andrew Lang&nbsp;... }}</ref>\n|[[Mark Twain]]\n|-\n|1925\n|''{{sort|Great Gatsby|[[The Great Gatsby]]}}''